<div style="background:#fff;"><div style="max-width:1000px;margin:0 auto;padding:8px 48px 56px;"><div style="margin-bottom:8px;"><div style="margin-bottom:26px;"><h2 style="font-family:var(--font-display);font-size:28px;font-weight:600;color:var(--ink);line-height:1.2;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin:0;">Frequently asked questions</h2></div>
    <div style="border:1px solid var(--line);border-radius:var(--radius-card);overflow:hidden;background:#fff;">
      <details class="sc-faq" open>
      <summary>When should I choose flip chip over wire bond?<span class="sc-faq-mk">+</span></summary>
      <div class="sc-faq-a">When you need the highest I/O density, the shortest electrical paths for RF or high-speed signals, or the lowest assembly profile. Flip chip replaces wire loops with direct bump joints between the die face and the substrate.</div>
    </details>
      <details class="sc-faq">
      <summary>What bump types and pitch do you handle?<span class="sc-faq-mk">+</span></summary>
      <div class="sc-faq-a">C4 solder bumps and copper pillars, with bump pitch down to 80 µm. Placement is face-down to ±10 µm, joined by mass reflow or thermo-compression bonding depending on the design.</div>
    </details>
      <details class="sc-faq">
      <summary>How is joint integrity verified?<span class="sc-faq-mk">+</span></summary>
      <div class="sc-faq-a">Non-destructively, on every assembly — 2D and 3D (CT) X-ray on the joint array, plus underfill void and fillet inspection. AEC-Q and IPC reliability testing is available in-house.</div>
    </details>
      <details class="sc-faq">
      <summary>What quality systems cover flip chip?<span class="sc-faq-mk">+</span></summary>
      <div class="sc-faq-a">ISO 9001 group-wide, IATF 16949 on automotive lines, ISO 13485 on medical. Assembly runs in ESD-controlled areas meeting ANSI/ESD S20.20.</div>
    </details>
      <details class="sc-faq">
      <summary>Do you protect customer designs and IP?<span class="sc-faq-mk">+</span></summary>
      <div class="sc-faq-a">An NDA is signed before any die, bump map, or CAD file is shared. Build areas are access-controlled and a program can be fenced to a dedicated line on request.</div>
    </details>
    </div>
